The article discusses the new National Space Policy, which outlines the executive branch's plan to advance United States interests in space. The policy aims to reaffirm the country's leadership in the space domain and recognizes space as a national imperative. The policy highlights the revival of the United States space enterprise, including the restoration of the capability to transport American astronauts to space on American rockets. The Artemis program is mentioned, which aims to return to the Moon and eventually explore Mars. The policy also emphasizes the encouragement and facilitation of the growth of the American commercial space sector. Additionally, it directs the United States to adapt its national security strategy to protect national interests in space, with the newly created Space Force enhancing the capabilities of the Armed Forces. The policy envisions a future of permanent human presence in space on the Moon, Mars, and beyond.